        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Leipzig,</placeName>
                    <date>Apr 5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1874.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I shall come to London to-morrow week and stay there till Wednesday after-noon. If I shall be able to see you this time, I am not quite sure, as I am rather pressed with my time. But on my return from Edinburgh<ref target="#foot.f1"/> in the beginning of August I shall try again to find you   This time I bring M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Carus and two daughters with me, whom I should not like to carry too-much about.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> So, if you should happen to hear from Dr Günther<ref target="#foot.f3"/> that I passed through London, pray excuse me if I did not try to pay you my respects personally, as I wished and have wished to do these many years</p>
<p>I am rather in haste, as it is always hard work to prepare work without one’s library and all the rest for four months coming.</p>
<p>Believe me to be | Yours always truly, | J. Victor Carus</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Carus gave a course of lectures on natural history at the University of Edinburgh (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9248.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. V. Carus, 19 January 1874</ref> and n. 2).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Carus’s wife was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5336.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sophie Catherine Carus</ref>. He had three daughters: Agnes Marie Elisabeth, Anne Sophie Gertrud, and Louise Charlotte Johanna.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1779.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Albert Günther</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
